docs.lead_paragraph: Months of rallying, handshaking and sign-waving reached an apex as the 2018 midterm elections came to an end on Tuesday. Democrats took control of the House of Representatives, but Republicans appeared likely to expand their majority in the Senate. Democrats also won in several governors’ races, but Republicans held on in swing states like Florida and Ohio. Several races around the country remained too close to call.

docs.abstract: A record number of lesbian, gay, bisexual or transgender candidates are running for office in November, as the Trump administration and state-level politicians have moved to roll back some legal protections.

docs.lead_paragraph: KANSAS CITY, Kan. — Sharice Davids, a leading Democrat in a key congressional primary election on Tuesday, finished a White House fellowship in the early months of the Trump administration. As a lesbian and a Native American, she became convinced that hard-won progress on issues like gay rights and the environment would erode under Mr. Trump, and thought Kansans in her district might support her as a counterforce to the president.
